6.84, "y0": 49.3, "x1": 70.85, "y1": 62.93}, {"x0": 48.6, "y0": 63.03, "x1": 68.53, "y1": 65.09}], "full_text": "Radiology\n2- Renal colic & obstructive uropathy\n• Present with Acute colicky flank pain\n• US → show renal stones and backpressure changes\n• KUB → detect only radio-dense stones\n•CT stone protocol → preferred modality to assess case\n3- Infection\n• Uncomplicated cases → diagnosed\nclinically with no imaging\n• Complicated infections → CT\n• One of serious infections is emphysematous\npyelonephritis\n(immuno-compromised diabetic by gas-forming\norganism) Axial CT post-contrast showing enlarged\nright kidney with heterogenous parenchyma\ncontaining air foci (similar density to the air\nin bowel loops)\n4- Testicular torsion\n• Present with Acute severe pain at\nipsilateral hemi-scrotum\n• Diagnosed clinical→ if unsure use\nUS\n• Doppler reduced vascularity\ncompared to other side, enlarged\nhypoechoic (darker) later\nTesticular torsion Normal Us & doppler\nheterogenous\nTake home messages\n• There are different imaging modalities to assess the genitourinary system each has its\nspecific indications and limitations\n• X-ray (KUB) is mainly to detect stones but their detailed assessment is done by CT\nstone protocol.\n• Ultrasound is the preferred modality to differentiate solid from cystic lesions (eg.\nrenal tumor and renal cyst)\n• The collecting system assessment can be done intravenous urogram (IVU) showing\nlesions as fixed (persistent) filling defects. This can also be done without the use of\n125"}